The two Poles
The European Parliament recently condemned the Polish government's attempt to remove Bronislaw Geremek from his parliamentary mandate.
Former leader of Solidarity, former political prisoner and former Foreign Minister - he led Poland's accession to NATO - Geremek refused to sign another new statement claiming he was not a secret police agent during the communist era.
European Parliamentarians spoke of a "witch hunt" regarding the Polish government's behavior, and Geremek stated that the law on denazification [decommunization] constitutes a threat to public freedoms.
In response, Polish Prime Minister Jaroslaw Kaczynski accused him of "harming the motherland" and of inciting anti-Polish sentiment.
The communists used the same words when Geremek criticized their abuse of power.
A constitutional court decision dated May 11 largely invalidated the denazification law, allowing Geremek to retain his seat in the European Parliament, at least for now.
But this law is part of a broader government policy aimed solely at weakening the country's institutions and democratic fabric.
What is happening in Poland, the country where the collapse of communism began?
Every revolution goes through two phases: first a struggle for freedom, then a fight for power.
The first is an emancipation of the human soul through which man expresses his best self, while the second frees the worst: envy, intrigues, greed, suspicion, and the desire for revenge.
The revolution triggered by the Polish union Solidarity followed an unusual trajectory.
Solidarity, forced into the underground when martial law was declared in December 1981, survived seven years of repression to reemerge in 1989, in the wake of Gorbachev's "perestroïka."
During the negotiations that ended the communist regime, Solidarity and the reformist wing of the communist government reached a compromise that paved the way for the peaceful dismantling of the communist dictatorship across the entire Soviet bloc.
Solidarity adopted a compromising attitude rather than vengeance, preferring the idea of a Poland for all rather than a country divided between all-powerful winners and oppressed losers.
Since 1989, there have been changes in government, but the country has remained stable. The former communists themselves have accepted the rules of parliamentary democracy and the market economy.
But not everyone has followed this path.
Today, Poland is governed by a coalition of post-Solidarity revenge-seekers, post-communist provincial disrupters, xenophobic and anti-Semitic groups, heirs to pre-war chauvinism, and circles surrounding Radio Maryja, the voice of ethno-clerical fundamentalism.
There are alarming signs everywhere: the authority of the judiciary is undermined, the independence of the Constitutional Tribunal is questioned, civil servants are bought, and the role of prosecutor is politicized.
Every day, social life is subjected to repressive regulation.
Why all of this?
Every successful revolution has its winners and losers.
The Polish revolution brought about public freedoms, but also increased crime, a market economy but also the risk of bankruptcy for businesses and high unemployment, as well as the emergence of a dynamic middle class, accompanied by a growing income gap.
It opened Poland to Europe, but it also instilled fear of the foreigner and fear of a mass invasion of Western culture.
For the losers of the 1989 Polish revolution, freedom comes with a lot of uncertainties.
In large companies, Solidarity workers became the victims of the freedoms they had won.
In the communist prison-like system, people were considered belonging to the State, but the State took care of them.
In a world of freedom, there is no one to take care of us.
It is in this atmosphere of anxiety that the ruling coalition governs, combining George Bush's conservative potion with Vladimir Putin's centralism.
Solidarity veterans believed that the end of the dictatorship would allow them to reach the heavens.
But the guilty among the communists were not punished and the virtuous Solidarity activists were not rewarded.
Thus, the feeling of injustice gave rise to resentment, envy, and a vengeful energy directed both against former enemies and old friends who seemed to benefit from the system.
The losers did not want to acknowledge that the conquest of freedom was the greatest success of Poland in 300 years.
For them, Poland remained a country governed by the communist security apparatus.
This Poland lacked a moral revolution that would ensure that crimes would not go unpunished, virtue would be rewarded, and injustices would be redressed.
After their victory in the general elections of 2005, the parties of the losers chose a method: a large purge.
According to the initial estimates, the lustration should take 17 years and affect 700,000 people.
A list of names was found in the archives of the security services; it will be made public.
And the 700,000 people destined for lustration must declare that they did not collaborate with the security services.
Those who refuse or make a false declaration must be dismissed and banned from practicing their profession for ten years.

The cardinal Dziwisz of Kraków reminds us that there is no place "for revenge, vengeance, lack of respect for human dignity, and unfounded accusations."
Never since the fall of communism has a cardinal used such strong words.
Should this lustration have taken place at the beginning of Poland's transformation? The goal of this peaceful revolution was freedom, sovereignty, and economic reforms, not a hunt for suspects—whether proven or not—of having belonged to the secret police.
If this hunt had taken place in 1990, neither the economic reforms of Leszek Balcerowicz nor the establishment of the rule of law would have been possible.
And Poland would not be a member of NATO, nor of the European Union.
Today, two Polands are facing each other.
The Poland of suspicion, fear, and revenge is fighting the Poland of hope, courage, and dialogue.
This Poland—made of openness and tolerance, the one of John Paul II and Czesław Milisz, of my friends from the underground and from prison—must prevail.
I believe that Poles will once again defend their right to be treated with dignity.
The Constitutional Tribunal's decision offers hope that the second phase of the Polish Revolution will not destroy what gave it birth, the desire for freedom, nor what it has generated, a democratic state.
